        DB::insert("
INSERT INTO `posts` (`id`, `title`, `body_markdown`, `body_html`, `slug`, `created_at`, `updated_at`, `header_attribution`, `published`) VALUES
(1, 'Quick. Hide the email address!',   'A [quick search](https://www.google.com/#q=javascript+email+address+obfuscation) for \"javascript email address obfuscation\" yielded a [stackoverflow answer](http://stackoverflow.com/a/748804/2483765) to URL encode it, along with comments about how that doesn\'t work.\r\nThe next result in Google was an [Email Address Obfuscator](http://www.albionresearch.com/misc/obfuscator.phpâ€Ž), which in my experience caused issues on mobile devices.\r\n\r\nAnother idea which is pretty common, is to use `myemailaddress at example dot com`. I don\'t like it because robots are smarter than that.\r\n\r\nThe next best thing is an image. Just type the email address into your favorite image processing program and voilÃ , you have an image to use instead of your email address.\r\nThen you have to deal with `:hover` effects of links. In my case, a color change as well as a slight background change. No sweat, put both versions in the image, and use the CSS `:hover` property to move the image up. \r\n\r\n![double-email-address-image](/img/blog/quick-hide-the-email-address/email.png \"Double Email Address Image\")\r\n\r\nNow, what do you put into the actual link? Either you can put `href=\"#\"`, but sometimes clicking it brings the user to the top of the page, which may not be what you want. So you need to put _something_ in there. What?\r\n\r\nI put this:\r\n\r\n```html\r\n<a href=\"mailto:404-Not-Found@example.com?subject=Hi!&amp;amp;body=Either type the email address or use the form. Thanks!\"></a>\r\n```\r\n\r\nOpening this link shows the following:\r\n\r\n![404-email-address](/img/blog/quick-hide-the-email-address/404-email-address.jpg \"404 Email Address\")\r\n\r\nGreat! So far so good. The last piece is the text _in_ the link. I used \"404 Not Found\".\r\n\r\nOne potential issue I realized is that on mobile devices, when users click the email link, they think it\'ll open up their email app using my real email address. It\'ll be a pain to go back to the browser, memorize the email address, go back to the mail app and type it in. The solution: hide the link on mobile devices (they can use the form).\r\n\r\n### Full source code:\r\n\r\n*HTML*\r\n\r\n```html\r\n<a href=\"mailto:404-Not-Found@example.com?subject=Hi!&amp;body=Either type the email address or use the form. Thanks!\" id=\"contact_email\">\r\n<span>404 Not Found</span>\r\n</a>\r\n```\r\n\r\n*CSS*\r\n\r\n```css\r\n@media (max-width: 992px) {\r\n #contact_email{ display: none; }\r\n}\r\n#contact_email span{\r\n   background-image: url(\"email.png\");\r\n   background-repeat: no-repeat;\r\n   display: block;\r\n height: 20px;\r\n   text-indent: -10000px;\r\n  width: 100%;\r\n}\r\n#contact_email:hover span{\r\n background-position: 0 -20px;\r\n}\r\n```', '<p>A <a href=\"https://www.google.com/#q=javascript+email+address+obfuscation\">quick search</a> for \"javascript email address obfuscation\" yielded a <a href=\"http://stackoverflow.com/a/748804/2483765\">stackoverflow answer</a> to URL encode it, along with comments about how that doesn\'t work.\r\nThe next result in Google was an <a href=\"http://www.albionresearch.com/misc/obfuscator.phpâ€Ž\">Email Address Obfuscator</a>, which in my experience caused issues on mobile devices.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Another idea which is pretty common, is to use <code>myemailaddress at example dot com</code>. I don\'t like it because robots are smarter than that.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The next best thing is an image. Just type the email address into your favorite image processing program and voilÃ , you have an image to use instead of your email address.\r\nThen you have to deal with <code>:hover</code> effects of links. In my case, a color change as well as a slight background change. No sweat, put both versions in the image, and use the CSS <code>:hover</code> property to move the image up. </p>\r\n\r\n<p><img src=\"/img/blog/quick-hide-the-email-address/email.png\" alt=\"double-email-address-image\" title=\"Double Email Address Image\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Now, what do you put into the actual link? Either you can put <code>href=\"#\"</code>, but sometimes clicking it brings the user to the top of the page, which may not be what you want. So you need to put <em>something</em> in there. What?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I put this:</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"highlight highlight-html\"><pre><span class=\"nt\">&lt;a</span> <span class=\"na\">href=</span><span class=\"s\">\"mailto:404-Not-Found@example.com?subject=Hi!&amp;amp;amp;body=Either type the email address or use the form. Thanks!\"</span><span class=\"nt\">&gt;&lt;/a&gt;</span>\r\n</pre></div>\r\n\r\n<p>Opening this link shows the following:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img src=\"/img/blog/quick-hide-the-email-address/404-email-address.jpg\" alt=\"404-email-address\" title=\"404 Email Address\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Great! So far so good. The last piece is the text <em>in</em> the link. I used \"404 Not Found\".</p>\r\n\r\n<p>One potential issue I realized is that on mobile devices, when users click the email link, they think it\'ll open up their email app using my real email address. It\'ll be a pain to go back to the browser, memorize the email address, go back to the mail app and type it in. The solution: hide the link on mobile devices (they can use the form).</p>\r\n\r\n<h3 id=\"fullsourcecode\">Full source code:</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><em>HTML</em></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"highlight highlight-html\"><pre><span class=\"nt\">&lt;a</span> <span class=\"na\">href=</span><span class=\"s\">\"mailto:404-Not-Found@example.com?subject=Hi!&amp;amp;body=Either type the email address or use the form. Thanks!\"</span> <span class=\"na\">id=</span><span class=\"s\">\"contact_email\"</span><span class=\"nt\">&gt;</span>\r\n    <span class=\"nt\">&lt;span&gt;</span>404 Not Found<span class=\"nt\">&lt;/span&gt;</span>\r\n<span class=\"nt\">&lt;/a&gt;</span>\r\n</pre></div>\r\n\r\n<p><em>CSS</em></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"highlight highlight-css\"><pre><span class=\"k\">@media</span> <span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"nt\">max-width</span><span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"nt\">992px</span><span class=\"o\">)</span> <span class=\"p\">{</span>\r\n    <span class=\"nf\">#contact_email</span><span class=\"p\">{</span> <span class=\"k\">display</span><span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"k\">none</span><span class=\"p\">;</span> <span class=\"p\">}</span>\r\n<span class=\"p\">}</span>\r\n<span class=\"nf\">#contact_email</span> <span class=\"nt\">span</span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\r\n    <span class=\"k\">background-image</span><span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"sx\">url(\"email.png\")</span><span class=\"p\">;</span>\r\n    <span class=\"k\">background-repeat</span><span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"k\">no-repeat</span><span class=\"p\">;</span>\r\n    <span class=\"k\">display</span><span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"k\">block</span><span class=\"p\">;</span>\r\n    <span class=\"k\">height</span><span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"m\">20px</span><span class=\"p\">;</span>\r\n    <span class=\"k\">text-indent</span><span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"m\">-10000px</span><span class=\"p\">;</span>\r\n    <span class=\"k\">width</span><span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"m\">100</span><span class=\"o\">%</span><span class=\"p\">;</span>\r\n<span class=\"p\">}</span>\r\n<span class=\"nf\">#contact_email</span><span class=\"nd\">:hover</span> <span class=\"nt\">span</span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\r\n    <span class=\"k\">background-position</span><span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"m\">0</span> <span class=\"m\">-20px</span><span class=\"p\">;</span>\r\n<span class=\"p\">}</span>\r\n</pre></div>', 'quick-hide-the-email-address', '2014-02-12 01:00:41',  '2014-02-25 22:29:49',  'photo credit: <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/26779385@N08/5690810225/\">Girls in Hunter Boots and more</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nd/2.0/\">cc</a>',    '2014-02-25 22:29:49')");
        DB::insert("INSERT INTO `posts` (`id`, `title`, `body_markdown`, `body_html`, `slug`, `created_at`, `updated_at`, `header_attribution`, `published`) VALUES (2, 'Lessons Learned From Sochi 2014',  'We are very proud of our athletes and their abilities. The sheer number of hours, the determination, and time and energy given up just to compete in the Olympics is worthy of mention.\r\n\r\nThat said, there was a decent amount of negativity surrounding the arrival of the athletes and other guests in the town of Sochi and its hotels. A [Twitter handle](https://twitter.com/SochiProblems) (which seems to have deleted all of its tweets, strange!) as well as countless articles and photos, all described some surprise and shock to Sochi\'s visitors.\r\n\r\nDespite all the negativity, and [there are some](http://deadspin.com/a-users-guide-to-the-bizarre-toilets-of-sochi-1516518904) who seek to explain everything, I think there are some business and management lessons we can all learn from. So, regardless whether this is true or false (I wasn\'t there), there are lessons to be had.\r\n\r\n1. Rooms not being ready. $51 Billion is no joke, as is a project the size of an Olympic village. There\'s a lot that goes into it, with more than 51 billion details. In short, it\'s a lot of work and complicated. It requires thorough organization and oversight. It requires making the right people in charge and giving them the space to make their own decisions. It also means making sure you leave yourself enough room should the deadline suddenly come closer. If possible, extend the deadline. In this case, a deadline extension is obviously out of the question. Well, how about imposing a pseudo-deadline a year earlier? And/or, having an inspection 6 months before the Olympics started?\r\n\r\n2. The toilets. Double toilets. A sign telling people not to flush uses toilet paper, instead put it in the waste basket. Well, in many areas of the globe this is normal. Fair enough. However, [as noted](http://deadspin.com/a-users-guide-to-the-bizarre-toilets-of-sochi-1516518904), $51 Billion should be enough to get some good, western-style piping in place. Besides that, the business lesson here is important: do your customer\'s expectations match your level of service? You may be offering something very acceptable in one industry or one location. But what is your customer expecting? It doesn\'t hurt to ask.\r\n\r\n3. [Sochi Hotel Changes A Man\'s Locks During The Opening Ceremony, Travel Nightmare Ensues](http://www.businessinsider.com/sochi-hotel-changes-locks-reporter-2014-2). It\'s hard to imagine a legitimate reason for [changing the locks](https://twitter.com/SeanFitz_Gerald/statuses/431905145044357121) on an already-occupied room. Whatever the reason, if you\'re going to change the locks on a room, should you inform the occupant? With regard to customer service, sometimes you need to make a change or do something (potentially) unpleasant. OK, that happens. But tell the customer first. Most people will be OK with you changing their locks as long as they know about it ahead of time.\r\n\r\nDo you agree?',  '<p>We are very proud of our athletes and their abilities. The sheer number of hours, the determination, and time and energy given up just to compete in the Olympics is worthy of mention.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>That said, there was a decent amount of negativity surrounding the arrival of the athletes and other guests in the town of Sochi and its hotels. A <a href=\"https://twitter.com/SochiProblems\">Twitter handle</a> (which seems to have deleted all of its tweets, strange!) as well as countless articles and photos, all described some surprise and shock to Sochi\'s visitors.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Despite all the negativity, and <a href=\"http://deadspin.com/a-users-guide-to-the-bizarre-toilets-of-sochi-1516518904\">there are some</a> who seek to explain everything, I think there are some business and management lessons we can all learn from. So, regardless whether this is true or false (I wasn\'t there), there are lessons to be had.</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n<li><p>Rooms not being ready. $51 Billion is no joke, as is a project the size of an Olympic village. There\'s a lot that goes into it, with more than 51 billion details. In short, it\'s a lot of work and complicated. It requires thorough organization and oversight. It requires making the right people in charge and giving them the space to make their own decisions. It also means making sure you leave yourself enough room should the deadline suddenly come closer. If possible, extend the deadline. In this case, a deadline extension is obviously out of the question. Well, how about imposing a pseudo-deadline a year earlier? And/or, having an inspection 6 months before the Olympics started?</p></li>\r\n<li><p>The toilets. Double toilets. A sign telling people not to flush uses toilet paper, instead put it in the waste basket. Well, in many areas of the globe this is normal. Fair enough. However, <a href=\"http://deadspin.com/a-users-guide-to-the-bizarre-toilets-of-sochi-1516518904\">as noted</a>, $51 Billion should be enough to get some good, western-style piping in place. Besides that, the business lesson here is important: do your customer\'s expectations match your level of service? You may be offering something very acceptable in one industry or one location. But what is your customer expecting? It doesn\'t hurt to ask.</p></li>\r\n<li><p><a href=\"http://www.businessinsider.com/sochi-hotel-changes-locks-reporter-2014-2\">Sochi Hotel Changes A Man\'s Locks During The Opening Ceremony, Travel Nightmare Ensues</a>. It\'s hard to imagine a legitimate reason for <a href=\"https://twitter.com/SeanFitz_Gerald/statuses/431905145044357121\">changing the locks</a> on an already-occupied room. Whatever the reason, if you\'re going to change the locks on a room, should you inform the occupant? With regard to customer service, sometimes you need to make a change or do something (potentially) unpleasant. OK, that happens. But tell the customer first. Most people will be OK with you changing their locks as long as they know about it ahead of time.</p></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>Do you agree?</p>', 'lessons-learned-from-sochi-2014',  '2014-02-25 22:31:07',  '2014-02-26 11:09:41',  'photo credit: <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/grant-condit/11432558884/\">Grant Condit</a> via <a href=\"http://photopin.com\">photopin</a> <a href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/2.0/\">cc</a>',  '2014-02-25 22:31:16')");
	}
}

class BusinessTableSeeder extends DatabaseSeeder
